    "Tony W. Cartledge": "Extrabiblical texts reveal the same pattern. Among the Amarna letters, there is one in\nwhich one \u201cAbdi-Asratu reported to the king: \u2018As I am a servant of the king and a dog of\nhis house, I guard all Amurru for the king, my lord\u2019 \u201c (Letter 60; see also 61).\nKyle McCarter cites a 14th century letter from Syria that asks: \u201cWho am I, some\ndog?\u201d, as well as a 6th century letter from Lachish that asks, \u201cWho is your servant, a\ndog, that my lord should have remembered his servant?\u201d (Lachish ostracon 2.4).\nThe metaphor used as an invective. There is one biblical example, also found in\n2 Samuel, in which David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s nephew and military henchman Abishai said to the king,\n\u201cWhy should this dead dog curse my lord the king? Let me go over and take off his\n[v_2Sa_16_9] head\u201d (2 Sam 16:9).\nExtrabiblical examples include a reference from the royal archives at Mari: \u201cWhat are\nthey? Dogs!\u201d (G. Dossin, Archives royales de Mari, I. no.27, I 28). Several examples\nappear in the Amarna letters, most in reference to one Abdi-Asirta, who is called\n\u201cservant and dog\u201d (Letter 71, 75, 85; see also 67).\nThe figure of a dog was used as a derogative in the New Testament period, as in Phil\n[v_Rev_22_15] 3:2: \u201cBeware of the dogs, beware of evil workers.\u201d Also, Rev 22:15 says, \u201cOutside are\nthe dogs and sorcerers and fornicators and murderers and idolaters, and everyone who\nloves and practices falsehood.\u201d\nAmarna texts from William L. Moran, ed. and trans., The Amarna Letters (Baltimore: Johns Hopkins University\nPress, 1992).\nP. Kyle McCarter, II Samuel (AB 9; Garden City: Doubleday, 1984),\nv. 13). News of this unexpected\ndevelopment forced the Ammonites to withdraw into their city\n("
