    "Tony W. Cartledge": "). For some unexplained reason, Joab did not pursue his\nadvantage, but presumably left enough soldiers to enforce a siege of\nRabbah.\nThe flight of the Arameans proved to have been a strategic with-\ndrawal, delaying the pitched battle until additional reinforcements\ncould be brought in from \u201cacross the river\u201d (vv. 15-16). Some\nscholars doubt the author intended the Euphrates, but there were\nmany Arameans in northwestern Mesopotamia during this period,\nso there is no real reason to propose that the Jordan, the Yarmuk, or\nthe Leontes Rivers were intended instead of the normal translation.\nThe newly strengthened Aramean armies then gathered for battle\nbehind Hadadezer\u2019s general, Shobach, at a place called Helam,\n[v_2Sa_10_1] [v_2Sa_10_2] [v_2Sa_10_3] [v_2Sa_10_4] [v_2Sa_10_5] [v_2Sa_10_6] [v_2Sa_10_7] [v_2Sa_10_8] [v_2Sa_10_9] [v_2Sa_10_10] [v_2Sa_10_11] [v_2Sa_10_12] [v_2Sa_10_13] [v_2Sa_10_14] [v_2Sa_10_15] [v_2Sa_10_16] [v_2Sa_10_17] [v_2Sa_10_18] [v_2Sa_10_19] 2 Samuel 10:1-19\n492\nWhere Did the Arameans Camp?\n[v_1Ch_19_6] [v_1Ch_19_7] The synoptic text in 1 Chr 19:6-7 includes additional information not found in\nthe MT, but also appearing in a shorter form in 4QSama.\nThe Chronicler\u2019s version shows clear signs of exaggeration. One thousand talents of\nsilver could have bought 100,000 slaves! The assertion that the king of Maacah and his\narmy camped before Medeba is problematic, because Medeba (some twenty miles\nsouth of Rabbah, over rugged terrain) seems too far south to offer the Ammonites much\nassistance, unless their purpose was to prevent an opportunistic Edomite invasion.\n[v_2Sa_10_6] 2 Samuel 10:6\n(6) When the Ammonites saw that they\nhad become odious to David `[char_David_Rut_4]`, the\nAmmonites sent and hired the\nArameans of Beth-rehob and the\nArameans of Zobah, twenty thousand\nfoot soldiers, as well as the king of\nMaacah, one thousand men, and the\nmen of Tob, twelve thousand men.\n[v_1Ch_19_6] [v_1Ch_19_7] 1 Chronicles 19:6-7\n(6) When the Ammonites say that they\nhad made themselves odious to David `[char_David_Rut_4]`,\nHanun and the Ammonites sent a\nthousand talents of silver to hire chariots\nand cavalry from Mesopotamia, from\nAram-maacah and from Zobah. (7) They\nhired thirty-two thousand chariots and\nthe king of Maacah with his army, who\ncame and camped before Medeba. And\nthe Ammonites were mustered from\ntheir cities and came to battle.\n493\n[v_2Sa_10_1] [v_2Sa_10_2] [v_2Sa_10_3] [v_2Sa_10_4] [v_2Sa_10_5] [v_2Sa_10_6] [v_2Sa_10_7] [v_2Sa_10_8] [v_2Sa_10_9] [v_2Sa_10_10] [v_2Sa_10_11] [v_2Sa_10_12] [v_2Sa_10_13] [v_2Sa_10_14] [v_2Sa_10_15] [v_2Sa_10_16] [v_2Sa_10_17] [v_2Sa_10_18] [v_2Sa_10_19] 2 Samuel 10:1-19\nwhich seems to have been a general region\nlocated in the Transjordanian plateau. [Helam\nand Other Places: David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s Battles with the Arameans]\nThere is no evidence that David `[char_David_Rut_4]` had par-\nticipated in the actual fighting of the first\nbattle since Joab and Abishai are portrayed as\nIsrael\u2019s military leaders. This time, however,\nDavid `[char_David_Rut_4]` led his army into battle, crossing the\nJordan further to the north than Joab had\ndone. This avoided the entrapment Joab had\nexperienced and also served to cut off the\nArameans from any Ammonite assistance.\nThe text insists that the two armies fought\nand David `[char_David_Rut_4]` won a great victory, killing huge\nnumbers of the enemy, including the famed\ngeneral Shobach (\nv. 14). [A Dangerous Dalliance]\nWith this stark prediction, the interview was\nover. Without entertaining questions or waiting\nto be dismissed, the sharp-tongued prophet\ndeparted. The narrator reports this with a\nstraightforward \u201cthen Nathan went to his\n[v_1Sa_24_22] house\u201d (12:15; cf. 1 Sam 24:22; 26:25).\n[v_2Sa_12_1] 2 Samuel 12:1-15a\n518\nTroublesome Terms\nNathan\u2019s prediction is fulfilled in 16:20-\nprophet Samuel told Saul that Yahweh would take\nthe kingdom away and give it to \u201ca neighbor\u201d who was\n[v_1Sa_15_28] better than he (1 Sam 15:28), so now Nathan insists that\nYahweh will give David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s wives to \u201ca neighbor,\u201d though there\nis no comment concerning the neighbor\u2019s worthiness. The\nword translated as \u201cneighbor\u201d technically refers to someone\nwho is close by, whether related or not.\n[v_2Sa_16_20] [v_2Sa_16_21] [v_2Sa_16_22] [v_2Sa_16_23] The story in 2 Sam 16:20-23 does not seem to match\nexactly, but this is a problem of terminology only. It seems\nthat Nathan expects David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s \u201cneighbor\u201d (who turns out to be\nhis son Absalom) to have the run of David `[char_David_Rut_4]`\u2019s entire harem,\nincluding his formal wives, but the account in 16:20-23\nmentions only certain concubines who were left behind to\nkeep house when David `[char_David_Rut_4]` fled the city. The word used in\n16:21-22 is a specific term for \u201cconcubines,\u201d while the term\nused by Nathan is the generic word for \u201cwoman,\u201d which\ncould also mean \u201cwife\u201d or \u201cconcubine\u201d in certain contexts.\nThus, Nathan\u2019s broad prediction could be fulfilled in a more\nnarrow way without calling his vocabulary into question.\nOne might also perceive a minor aberration in Nathan\u2019s\nclaim that the \u201cneighbor\u2019s\u201d erotic activity would take place\nin broad daylight (12:11; lit., \u201cbefore the eyes of this sun\u201d),\nfor the text says that Absalom had a tent pitched on the roof\nof the palace, beneath which he took his father\u2019s concubines\nas a sign that he also had taken the kingdom. Nathan\u2019s\nidiomatic intent is obviously that the thing be done in public\nview, as 16:22 expressly declares that the deed was done\n\u201cin the sight of all Israel.\u201d Nathan\u2019s meaning is further\nclarified by"
